'''Spin Chemistry''' is a sub-field of [[chemistry]] and [[physics]], positioned at the intersection of [[chemical kinetics]], [[photochemistry]], [[magnetic resonance]] and [[free radical]] chemistry, and dealing with magnetic and [[spin (physics)|spin]] effects in chemical reactions. The examples of phenomena that '''Spin Chemistry''' deals with are Chemically Induced Dynamic Nuclear and Electron Polarization ([[CIDNP]] and [[CIDEP]]), magnetic [[isotope]] effects in chemical reactions, as well as the environmental and health effects of static and oscillating electromagnetic [[Field (physics)|fields]].
Some of the prominent scientists in the field (in alphabetical order) are:
*E. G. Bagryanskaya (Novosibirsk, Russia), *K.-P. Dinse (Darmstadt, Germany), *S. A. Dzuba (Novosibirsk, Russia), *M. D. E. Forbes (Chapel Hill, USA), *P. Gast (Leiden, Netherlands), *P. J. Hore (Oxford, UK), *G. Jeschke (Mainz, Germany), *R. Kaptein (Utrecht, Netherlands), *C. W. M. Kay (Berlin, Germany), *K. Möbius (Berlin, Germany), *Yu. N. Molin (Novosibirsk, Russia), *J. R. Norris (Chicago, USA), *R. Z. Sagdeev (Novosibirsk, Russia), *K. M. Salikhov (Kazan, Russia), *U. Steiner (Konstanz, Germany), *S. Tero-Kubota (Sendai, Japan), *C. R. Timmel (Oxford, UK), *A. J. van der Est (St. Catharines, Canada) *H.-M. Vieth (Berlin, Germany), *S. Weber (Berlin, Germany).
==See also== The [http://spinportal.chem.ox.ac.uk/ spin chemistry portal].
