A '''Wien filter''' is a device consisting of perpendicular [[electric]] and [[magnetic]] fields that can be used as a velocity filter for charged particles, for example in [[electron microscope|electron microscopes]] and spectrometers.<ref name=rose/><ref name=Galejs1978>{{cite journal|last = Galejs|first = A.|year = 1978|title = Focusing and dispersing properties of a stigmatic crossed-field energy analyzer|journal = Journal of Vacuum Science and Technology|volume = 15|pages = 865|doi = 10.1116/1.569615|url=http://cnst.nist.gov/epg/Pubs/pdf/epg373.pdf|format=free-download pdf}}</ref> It is named for [[Wilhelm Wien]] who developed it in 1898 for the study of [[anode rays]].<ref name='Wien_1898'>{{cite journal|journal=Ann. der Physik|first=W.|last=Wien|volume=65|pages=440}}</ref><ref name=Wien1999>{{cite journal|last = Wien|first = Karl|year = 1999|title = 100 years of ion beams: Willy Wien's canal rays|journal = Brazilian Journal of Physics|volume = 29|doi = 10.1590/S0103-97331999000300002|url=http://www.sbfisica.org.br/bjp/files/v29_401.pdf|format=free-download pdf}}</ref> It can be configured as a charged particle energy analyzer, [[monochromator]], or [[mass spectrometer]].<ref name=Galejs1978 /><ref name=rose>{{cite journal| doi= 10.1088/0031-8949/9/1/014107|title=Optics of high-performance electron Microscopes|format=free download review on electron optics|volume= 9|year= 2008| author= H. H. Rose| journal= Science and Technology of Advanced Materials| pages= 014107}}</ref>

